104
00:07:46,960 --> 00:07:50,579
"I'm truly sorry that I couldn't publish Volume 2"

105
00:07:52,139 --> 00:07:55,940
"However..." What did Professor Imai say after this?

106
00:07:56,780 --> 00:07:59,640
Please watch the full video to find out

107
00:08:00,920 --> 00:08:03,540
Professor Imai's conviction as a researcher

108
00:08:04,300 --> 00:08:06,660
Mr. Ono's sense of mission as an editor

109
00:08:07,310 --> 00:08:08,460
You can feel them both

110
00:08:09,780 --> 00:08:12,160
I was deeply moved

111
00:08:13,199 --> 00:08:16,220
The table of contents for the non-existent Volume 2

112
00:08:16,780 --> 00:08:18,679
is not just a table of contents

113
00:08:18,700 --> 00:08:23,460
It represents Professor Imai's passion for fluid mechanics itself

114
00:08:24,640 --> 00:08:31,000
You could say it's homework that Professor Imai left for us

115
00:08:32,080 --> 00:08:35,760
That's why this table of contents remains to this day

116
00:08:36,700 --> 00:08:44,139
I was moved to see that this is the work of editors, the unsung heroes of knowledge transmission

117
00:08:45,360 --> 00:08:53,040
We can still read books published over 50 years ago thanks to the work of editors

118
00:08:54,340 --> 00:09:01,560
We tend to think that human knowledge has progressed continuously throughout history

119
00:09:02,400 --> 00:09:09,120
But that's not true at all. Historically, much knowledge has been lost

120
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:31,000
For example, the Library of Alexandria. This library was built in the 3rd century BC in what is now Alexandria, Egypt, and housed various books recording the knowledge of Greek civilization at the time. However, this library lost a vast amount of knowledge due to financial difficulties and wars.

121
00:09:32,280 --> 00:09:44,120
A more familiar example would be broken links to references in blog posts from 10 years ago. Even events from just 10 years ago are difficult to trace accurately now

122
00:09:45,060 --> 00:09:59,959
Knowledge is easily lost without effort to maintain it. Publishers and editors do the tremendously important work of passing knowledge on to the next generation

